{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488692"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:52:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"507"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/507"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.21,0.02,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107191"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/507"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"507"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89644"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"319"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43965"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107191"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of severe pain in her left eye associated with blurred vision and nausea. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. Her visual acuity is \u0027count fingers\u0027 in the left eye and 6/9 in the right. There is conjunctival injection of the vessels in the left eye, and further examination is difficult due to corneal haze. The left pupil is mid-dilated and poorly reactive to light. On two-finger palpation, the left eye feels much firmer than the right. Intraocular pressure measurement confirms raised pressure in the left eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous acetazolamide","Topical pilocarpine","Topical steroid drops","Intravenous hydrocortisone","Atropine eyedrops"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms and signs of acute angle closure glaucoma (AACG), including severe eye pain, blurred vision, nausea, conjunctival injection, corneal haze, a mid-dilated and poorly reactive pupil, and increased intraocular pressure. AACG is an ophthalmic emergency that requires immediate treatment to lower intraocular pressure and preserve vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous acetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. It rapidly reduces intraocular pressure by decreasing aqueous humor production and promoting its outflow. This systemic carbonic anhydrase inhibitor is effective in quickly lowering eye pressure in AACG.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical pilocarpine\u003C/strong\u003E stimulates miosis (pupil constriction), which can help to open the angle and further decompress the eye. However, it is usually administered after initial pressure-lowering with acetazolamide, as very high intraocular pressures can make pilocarpine less effective due to transient iris sphincter ischemia. Though can be used during the acute attack, and certainly as a prophylaxis against further attacks, it is less effective in lowering eye pressure when compared with systemic acetazolamide. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical steroid drops\u003C/strong\u003E are helpful to aid in controlling the associated inflammation with AACG and clear the cornea for further intervention like laser peripheral iridotomy, however they are not considered first line of treatment. They are used as an adjunct treatment after breaking the initial angle closure attack\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hydrocortisone\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in the acute management of AACG. While topical steroids may be used later to reduce inflammation, systemic steroids are not a first-line treatment for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtropine eyedrops\u003C/strong\u003E dilate the pupil for 7-14 days. They are contraindicated in this case as they may further exacerbate angle closure and worsen the patient\u0027s condition. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial management with intravenous acetazolamide, additional treatments may include topical beta-blockers to further suppress aqueous humor production, and topical alpha-2 agonists. Definitive treatment often involves laser peripheral iridotomy once the acute attack is controlled. It\u0027s crucial to recognize and treat AACG promptly to prevent permanent vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The diagnosis of acute angle closure glaucoma requires prompt treatment to lower intraocular pressure and preserve eyesight.","Intravenous acetazolamide is the first-line treatment for acute angle closure glaucoma to rapidly reduce intraocular pressure.","Topical pilocarpine is used as a second-line treatment in acute angle closure glaucoma to stimulate miosis and further open the angle."],"references":["Chan PP, Pang JC, Tham CC. Acute primary angle closure\u2013treatment strategies, evidences and economical considerations. Eye. 2019; 33:110-19. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6328531/","Primary vs. Secondary Angle Closure Glaucoma - EyeWiki. eyewiki.org. https://eyewiki.org/Primary_vs._Secondary_Angle_Closure_Glaucoma"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89644"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"507"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89644"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T22:25:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T23:02:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"507"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"